This paper is likely to belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) sub-category as it discusses the use of non-convex optimization with local search heuristics in machine learning and achieving state-of-the-art results. It also mentions unsupervised learning and learning latent variable models, which are common topics in machine learning. 

The paper also uses random matrix theory and Kac-Rice formula, which are commonly used in information theory (cs.IT) and numerical analysis (cs.NA). 

The analysis of the optimization landscape of the random over-complete tensor decomposition problem involves studying the geometry of the objective function, which is related to the study of high-dimensional spaces and their structures, making it relevant to the data structures (cs.DS) sub-category. 

Finally, the paper discusses the counting of local minima of a highly-structured random polynomial with dependent coefficients, which is related to the study of random structures (cs.SI).
